            {
               "text": "<h3>The Size of the Earth</h3>The understanding that the Earth is spherical dates back thousands of years. The ancient Greeks reached this conclusion by observing how ship masts disappeared over the horizon and by noting the Earth’s shadow cast on the Moon during lunar eclipses. However, these observations did not provide a precise measurement of the Earth’s roundness. The first confirmed measurement was made around <htdate0> by Eratosthenes. On the summer solstice, he observed that in the city of Syene, the Sun’s rays reached straight to the bottom of a well, while in Alexandria, a pole cast a shadow pointing south. By knowing the properties of circles and the distance between Alexandria and Syene, Eratosthenes calculated the Earth’s circumference to be around 40,000 kilometers",
               "source": [
                  {
                     "type": 1,
                     "uuid": "7b82ec3f-a292-48b4-8945-58e2d154f499",
                     "text": "Brown, Cynthia S",
                     "page": "",
                     "date_time": {
                        "type": "gregory",
                        "year": "2024",
                        "month": "10",
                        "day": "27"
                     }
                  }
               ],
               "date_time": [
                  {
                     "type": "gregory",
                     "year": "-240",
                     "month": "-1",
                     "day": "-1"
                  }
               ],
               "isTable": false,
               "imgdesc": "",
               "format": "html",
               "PostMention": "."
            },
            {
               "text": "<h3>The Earth's Diameter</h3>More than 1,000 years later, Eratosthenes' calculations were confirmed under the authority of an Abbasid Caliph. A more precise measurement of the Earth’s meridians, and consequently of its radius, was carried out later by Al-Biruni. For his measurements, Al-Biruni was in Kath during a lunar eclipse, recording the event’s timing, while his colleague Abu’l-Wafa made observations in Baghdad. Additionally, Al-Biruni used the distances of caravan routes to determine the difference in longitude between Baghdad and Ghazni. With this data, he estimated the Earth’s radius to be approximately 6,371 kilometers, corresponding to an angle of 24 degrees at a latitude of 33 degrees north—a value that matches the Earth's average radius",
               "source": [
                  {
                     "type": 1,
                     "uuid": "bd3c511d-a7c6-4720-9956-b863578fe58b",
                     "text": "Sparavigna, Amelia C.",
